1. DNS Resolution – Amazon Route 53
User enters the domain → Route 53 resolves it to the CloudFront distribution endpoint.
2. Edge Layer – Amazon CloudFront (SSL Termination)
Request reaches nearest edge location
SSL certificate (from AWS Certificate Manager) is validated

SSL/TLS handshake happens:
CloudFront provides public key
Browser establishes secure session (session key)
Communication becomes encrypted (HTTPS)
CloudFront decrypts request (SSL termination)

Checks cache:
If cached → response returned instantly
If not → forwards request to backend

3. External Load Balancer – Application Load Balancer
Receives request from CloudFront
Performs Layer 7 routing:
Path-based (/api, /login)
Host-based routing
Runs health checks

Routes traffic to Web Tier

4. Web Tier (Frontend Layer)
EC2 instances running Nginx/Apache
Responsibilities:
Handle incoming HTTP requests
Serve static content
Forward dynamic requests

5. Internal Load Balancer – Application Load Balancer
Private (not internet-facing)
Routes traffic from Web Tier to App Tier

Ensures secure internal communication

6. Application Tier (Monolithic Logic)
Single codebase handling:
Authentication
Business logic
API processing

Scales horizontally using Auto Scaling

🗄️ 7. Database Tier – Amazon RDS
Runs in private subnet
Access restricted to App Tier only
Supports Multi-AZ for high availability

8. Response Flow

DB → App → Internal ALB → Web → ALB → CloudFront → User

📌 CloudFront may cache response for faster future access
